snippet.textDisplay:
There has always been debates on Cats the musical, and no one in or out of the theatre fandom doesn’t have an opinion on it, personally I believe it should stay on Broadway just like musicals like Les Miserables and Phantom (if that was made into a good movie), it isn’t supposed to make sense, that’s the sense of it. It purposefully hurts your mind to think about the story and I definitely think some of the songs go on for way too long, like Gus the Theatre Cats, I watched it in a theatre and I was waiting for it to be over for so long I thought the musical would’ve been done after the song was, it’s meant for an audience that somehow understands it and being in the musical theatre fandom, it doesn’t make it into my top 10 just because it’s too confusing at times.

That being said Ellen Page is amazing and if she performed as Grizabella in the movie it would’ve been brilliant, not to say that the actress didn’t do an amazing job at playing her already

snippet.textDisplay: The original musical is 18th century poetry about cats with absolutely no talking. The original agreement in order to make this a musical was simply not to add or subtract any words to it so they had to do their best with that to make it have some sort of plot. Sir Andrew Lloyd Webber is the composer so I would say the music is far from cheap. Yes it is entirely hard to understand if you don’t know the history behind it and it is “ugly” it’s like watching when Pixar and dreamworks haven’t quite finished their animations. The movie does provide more plot than the musical, by far. I would read up on the musical before you have any business going to see it and maybe wait for it to go to Netflix or some other streaming platform, personally.

snippet.textDisplay: Well personally I expected much worse than what I got. I love the stage production and the original poems, and was able to follow everything that was going on. I think another director and either more time for post production to FINISH THEIR WORK would have served it well. The thing that has kept the stage version running all these years is that it's 2 and a half hours of almost continuous singing and dancing. The physicality alone is spectacular. Most performers have said that Cats is the most physically challenging show they have ever done, and usually have to switch to another show for a few months just to recuperate from how demanding it is. Nonetheless, I've heard the dancers say they love the experience performing it every time. All I can hope is that the careers of all those involved in the movie recover, and that the show will keep going. Cats was a gamble as a book and a stage show, and those gambles paid off exponentially. Third time may not have been a charm, but I'm sincerely hoping it didn't ruin anything. I think the movie, for all its flaws, did have a lot of good aspects too. And maybe once the drama has died down, people will be able to appreciate those things more, should they dare to watch it again. Me, I'm getting the DVD and putting it next to the '98 filmed version. It's because if this movie that I looked into what Cats was about at all. I've made some amazing friends and we've created amazing things within the fandom. I love Cats, and I'm satisfied.
